    • nextASCIICharSeq

      public static String nextASCIICharSeq(int length)
      Comes up with a String instance consisting of ASCII printing characters. This means the String won't contain any ASCII control characters like Data Link Escape (U+0010) or Delete (U+007F).
      Parameters:
      length - How long to make the String. For example, 12.
      Returns:
      A String instance of ASCII printing characters. Note that the straight single and double quote can occur in the results. Examples for length being 12: "]Vv36l"o'eVA", "KYY>xld?J[Zw", "aWG[Q B:_3aY" and "gk|0++euubinvalid input: '&v'".
      Throws:
      NegativeArraySizeException - If length is negative.

    • nextInt

      public static int nextInt(int bound)
      Gives a pseudorandomly chosen integer up to a given bound.
      Parameters:
      bound - The bound to go up to. For example, 100.
      Returns:
      An integer equal to at least 0 but not equal to bound but not greater than that. For example, 22.

    • nextPowerOfTwo

      public static int nextPowerOfTwo()
      Gives a pseudorandomly chosen power of two. The number is always positive, it's never Integer.MIN_VALUE.
      Returns:
      A power of 2, at least 1, at most 1073741824, which is 230. For example, 524288, which is 219.

    • nextObject

      public static <E> E nextObject(E[] array)
      Chooses an element of an array pseudorandomly. With enough calls, every element of the array should be given at least once.
      Type Parameters:
      E - The type of the elements in the array. For example, java.time.DayOfWeek.
      Parameters:
      array - An array of objects of type E. For example, MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY and two nulls, corresponding to the DayOfWeek.values() array with SUNDAY and SATURDAY changed to null.
      Returns:
      One element of the array, chosen pseudorandomly. For example, WEDNESDAY. May be null, since an array can contain nulls.
      Throws:
      NoSuchElementException - If the array has no elements.

    • nextObject

      public static <E> E nextObject(List<E> list)
      Chooses an element of a list pseudorandomly. With enough calls, every element of the list should be given at least once.
      Type Parameters:
      E - The type of the elements in the list. For example, java.time.DayOfWeek.
      Parameters:
      list - A list of objects of type E. For example, TUESDAY, SUNDAY, FRIDAY, WEDNESDAY, MONDAY, SATURDAY, THURSDAY, TUESDAY, etc. (these are the days of the day of the week of February 29 in the leap years since the start of Unix time on through the year 2024).
      Returns:
      One element of the list, chosen pseudorandomly. For example, SATURDAY. May be null, since a list can contain nulls.
      Throws:
      NoSuchElementException - If the list has no elements.

    • nextObject

      public static <E> E nextObject(Set<E> set)
      Chooses an element of a set pseudorandomly. With enough calls, every element of the set should be given at least once.
      Type Parameters:
      E - The type of the elements in the list. For example, java.lang.Integer.
      Parameters:
      list - A list of objects of type E. For example, {0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 6, 19, 21, 10, 24, 15} (these are the squares modulo 30).
      Returns:
      One element of the set, chosen pseudorandomly. For example, 19. May be null, since a set in Java is allowed to have one null.
      Throws:
      NoSuchElementException - If the set has no elements.
